<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: MAN CHARGED IN FORGERY OF TAX REFUND CHECK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Culver City man accused of trying to steal more than $644,000 from the state 
by adding a few extra digits to his tax refund check was charged Thursday with 
forgery and attempted grand theft. 
</P>
<P>
State officials, who said the case is one of the largest of its kind in state 
history, say Mathison B. Coleman, 56, allegedly increased the amount of his 
$33.62 state refund check to $644,933.62 before submitting it to his bank in 
Manhattan Beach. 
</P>
<P>
"Now wasn't that chutzpah? Can you believe it? This is classic. I've never seen 
a case like this," said Deputy Dist. Atty. Gilbert Garcetti, who heads the 
district attorney's Torrance branch. 
</P>
<P>
Coleman, who was scheduled to turn himself in to Manhattan Beach police this 
morning, faces up to three years in state prison if convicted. His attorney, 
Robert Corbin, declined to comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
FORGERY; TAX REFUNDS; INCOME TAX FRAUD 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
