<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: DEA SCANDAL BEGAN WITH $16,000 THEFT, JURY 
TOLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A federal prosecutor said in a Los Angeles courtroom Thursday that a Drug 
Enforcement Administration corruption scandal began with the theft of $16,000 
in drug cash in October, 1982, leading to narcotics trafficking charges being 
filed against three agents. 
</P>
<P>
From that point, Asst. U.S. Atty. 
</P>
<P>
Stefan D. Stein said, the agents engaged "in a spree of corruption" that led to 
a federal grand jury indictment two years ago charging them, among other 
things, with stealing drugs from the DEA's evidence vault in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
Two of the agents have pleaded guilty. The trial of the third agent, Darnell 
Garcia, 43, of Rancho Palos Verdes, is set to begin Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
Jury selection was completed Thursday and Stein's co-prosecutor, Asst. U.S. 
Atty. Joyce Karlin, said she expects the trial to last about two months. As he 
was leaving the courtroom of U.S. District Judge Terry J. Hatter Jr., Garcia 
was asked by a reporter if he was confident of acquittal. "Yeah, a lot," he 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
