<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
HACKER THREATS DON'T COME TRUE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Telephone companies reported normal operations today after bracing for a 
possible disruption of service somewhere in the country by computer "hackers" 
breaking into the phone network. 
</P>
<P>
Non-specific threats had been made to invade the massive computers that control 
the telephone network but not to attack physical facilities, industry sources 
said. 
</P>
<P>
The sources said the threats apparently were in connection with the sentencing, 
scheduled in Atlanta this afternoon, of three members of a hackers' group 
called the Legion of Doom who had broken into BellSouth Corp. computers. But by 
late morning Eastern time, no problems had been reported. 
</P>
<P>
"This has been a normal weekday, and there's been no indication of trouble 
anywhere in the network," said Herb Linnen, a spokesman for American Telephone 
&amp; Telegraph. 
</P>
</TEXT>
